  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">FAQs</span><h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Sovereign Gold Bonds</h2></div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>What is the lock-in period for Sovereign Gold Bonds?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>SGBs have a tenure of 8 years with an exit option after the 5th year. Early redemption with RBI is allowed on coupon payment dates after the 5th year. However, you can sell SGBs on the stock exchange at any time after listing (usually 2 weeks after issue). Selling on the exchange before 8 years means capital gains are taxable.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>How is the interest on SGBs taxed?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>The 2.5% annual interest is added to your total income and taxed at your applicable slab rate. However, no TDS is deducted at source. Capital gains at maturity (8 years) are completely tax-free. If sold before maturity on exchanges, short-term gains (under 12 months) are taxed at slab rate, and long-term gains at 12.5% with indexation.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Can NRIs invest in Sovereign Gold Bonds?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>No, SGBs are restricted to resident individuals, HUFs, trusts, universities, and charitable institutions. NRIs are not eligible to subscribe to SGBs. However, if a resident who bought SGBs subsequently becomes an NRI, they can continue to hold the bonds until maturity or early redemption.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>What is the maximum investment limit for SGBs?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>The minimum investment is 1 gram of gold. The maximum limit per fiscal year is 4 kg for individuals and HUFs, and 20 kg for trusts and similar entities. This limit applies to the total investment across all SGB tranches in a financial year, including purchases from the secondary market.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Is SGB better than physical gold or gold ETFs?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>SGBs offer several advantages: 2.5% annual interest (gold ETFs/physical gold pay nothing), tax-free capital gains at maturity, sovereign guarantee, no storage cost, and no making charges or GST. Gold ETFs charge an expense ratio of 0.5%–1% annually. Physical gold has making charges (8%–25%), GST (3%), and storage/insurance costs. For investment purposes, SGBs are clearly superior to other gold options.</p></div></div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

